segments.text: On Thursday, she got back on the bus from Tel Aviv to home.
She dozed heavily the whole way, her head resting against the window, banging against it repeatedly.
She was so tired, it was exam season, and she was going to bed very late every night.
She didn't know what awaited her at home.
Would Yosef be there, or would she find a note on the door saying he'd be gone for two or three days?
In any case, the task of cleaning the rooms and the dining room awaited her, as it had in recent months.
Unlike usual, recently she found one or two rooms especially messy and dirty.
Towels thrown on the floor, empty beer bottles, and ashtrays full of cigarettes.
The tenants were fairly regular.
They came to the hotel after a workday, including doctors, veterinarians, truck drivers and engineers.
There weren't many, but enough to fill a few rooms.
Sometimes not even that.
She would find their rooms almost as she left them, as if they came in the evening, just laid their heads on a pillow and fell asleep.
Some had a book lying by the bed.
and she would try to guess their nature by its content.
Who preferred thrillers?
Who romance?

And even the aftershave on the bathroom shelf categorized them in her eyes, those of brute, those of aqua-velva, and suddenly, as if someone foreign had invaded one of the rooms, leading chaos and a slightly cheat scent behind.
She said nothing to Yosef.
She knew well he was uncomfortable with her cleaning instead of the regular cleaners who used to work for them.
He never asked her to do it.
She took it upon herself every time.
Understanding this wasn't how the house should be.
Now, with Fortuna not coming at all, he occasionally called Julie, who used to work for them regularly.
Julie was a sturdy, short-haired girl who came to the pink house at least once a week, each time for a few hours, to clean the dining room, kitchen.
and rooms, but when Yosef disappeared for days, no one would clean.
Along with the note she'd find on the door and newspapers tucked underneath, it was clear the sheets needed changing, and the rooms, dining room, and Lucy's garden needed attention.
It wasn't hard for her.
She'd tackle the house, finishing everything in two hours, from top to bottom, delighting in the clean scent around.
It was almost therapeutic for her.
Nonetheless, due to the accumulated fatigue, she hoped Julie had been there recently, so at least part of this would be spared her.
At the central station, she boarded another bus home and ten minutes later, duty the driver, smiling, announced, the pink house stop.
He stopped at her house and waved goodbye.
She got off slowly, almost dragging her bag of books and notebooks, thinking of studying over the weekend.
She stood for a moment by the station bench to arrange her belongings, and when she lifted her head, she suddenly saw Julie sitting at the end of the bench crying.
She immediately sat next to her, putting her arm around her, and asked, What happened, Julie?
Are you not feeling well?
Come home with me.
Have something to drink.
Julie didn't answer.
Just shook her head no, unable to speak.
She sat with her quietly for a few more minutes and then said, Tell me what happened.
You can tell me.
I'm a big girl now.
You're not here.
You don't see what's going on.
It's not good what's happening here.
If Lucy saw she die again, she said and fell silent.
What are you talking about?
I know he disappears for days, but look, it's hard for him to.
Everything's falling apart.
There's no money and there aren't many guests and he wants to get out and unwind.
I come on weekends, clean, organize and leave everything tidy.
So it's okay for a few days.
No, Julie said in a cracked voice.
I know, but your father, maybe because he really doesn't have enough money is renting rooms to people who come for a few hours and bring girls.
I don't want to clean after such people.
I'm not coming back.
I'm crying now because there was an old man there who wanted to pay me to stay with him in the room, and I ran away.
She was in complete shock, replaying.
In her mind, those especially dirty rooms and hadn't realized why and knew Julie was telling the truth.
Is he home?
She asked carefully.
No, he left yesterday and forgot to tell me not to come.
So I came," she replied.
Come, come home with me.
We'll sit and drink something, then you can go.
I'm so sorry.
I had no idea.
I saw some messy rooms, but didn't understand.
Maybe I'm still a little kid.
Don't worry, it won't happen again.
If you want, come.
And if you don't, then don't.
Does he owe you money?
No, Julie said.
Joseph is a good man.
He always pays me on time, sometimes even more than he should.
Maybe he just needed money and didn't know what to do.
Julie softened towards him now as well.
A little while later, after giving Julia a drink and sending her on her way, she sat amazed at the table, trying to shake off the impact of this story.
Suddenly, she stood up, gathered the cleaning supplies, sheets, and towels, and headed to the room area.
The doors of two rooms were ajar, and a key stuck outside.
She realized immediately these were the rooms where something had tarnished them.
And indeed, the sight that greeted her was not pleasant.
With a burst of crazy energy, she attacked them, pouring bleach and cleaning powder on the sanitary fixtures.
attacking the room with water and soap, mopping it out, changing all the sheets and towels, opening the windows and shutters, leaving the rooms to air out from their defilement.
Fresh air should enter them, and a breeze should cleanse them.
When she finished, she moved all the sheets and towels to the large concrete sink behind the kitchen.
filled it with water and a whole box of bio-ore powder and a chunk of laundry soap and left them to soak.
She'd come back later to wash and hang them.

Only then, soaked, did she make her way to her private shower, standing under the water stream, scrubbing herself from head to toe, washing her hair vigorously, feeling her nails almost dig into her flesh, trying to cleanse herself from this story too.
In the late hours of that evening, as she stood behind the bar, pouring herself a cup of coffee with milk, the door suddenly opened and Yosef stood at the entrance, smiling at her lovingly.
Leora emerged from behind the bar with a frozen expression, not approaching him.
And as he closed the few meters between them, she couldn't hold back.
So now it's turning into a brothel?
Before she understood what was happening, he slapped her hard on the face.
In terrible shock, she found her hand cradling her burning cheek.
Never in her life had anyone raised a hand against her.
There had never been a reason.
This was her daddy, who loved her so much, even if sometimes in his own way.
And the slap scorched her soul much more than her cheek.
He was as shocked as she was.
His face was pale and his jaw clenched.
Neither of them moved, standing there with the clear knowledge that both had crossed a red line.
She had spoken so bluntly what was on her mind, and he, the sentence she threw at him, was like a punch to the center of his heart, causing him to lose control.
They stood there upright and pale, feelings of insult and shame mixing together, until he crossed the centimeters between them and hugged her tightly to his heart.
Do you want coffee?
She asked once they calmed a bit.
I just made some.
I think we could use something a bit stronger," he answered with a half-smile.
He poured himself a small glass of cognac and hurra campari with oranges, and they sat next to each other at the bar, leaning against each other.
He lifted his head and looked into her eyes.
Look, sweetheart, there's a huge money problem because of the receivership imposed on us.
And I thought it wouldn't hurt to rent a room or two by the hour to bring in some income.
I didn't think they'd bring dubious women.
I thought couples might come who have nowhere else to be, and it didn't seem so bad to me.
This whole story is only from the last month.
I already noticed it two weeks ago, but I guess it was convenient for me to turn a blind eye knowing it's profitable.
She couldn't hold back.
Maybe if you thought about the fact that someone has to clean after them and how they leave the rooms, it would have shocked you a bit, she said.
And in the same breath, she told him about the indecent proposal Julie received, who ran away as fast as she could and told her she wouldn't return.
Joseph looked like someone who had gone through a hard jolt.
She wasn't sure if it was from what was said in their conversation or from that slap he gave her.
Perhaps both.
This house is falling apart in my hands and I'm running out of solutions.
I've run out of tricks, but apparently some options should never be used, he told her.
She felt the drink spreading through her body, calming her and slowly regulating her breathing.
It'll be okay daddy," she said, laying her head on his shoulder and deep inside.
She'd already realized that perhaps it really wouldn't be.
